#This makes it possible to distinguish between cells where only the cuckoo was observed, cells where only the host species were present, and cells where the cuckoo co-occurred with one or both host species. 
#The red cells, where Cuculus canorus co-occurs with both Prunella modularis and Acrocephalus scirpaceus, can be interpreted as potential hotspots of parasite–host interaction. 
#These areas are mainly concentrated in western and central Europe, suggesting that environmental conditions and host availability in these regions may be particularly favourable for the cuckoo.
#The orange and purple cells indicate areas where the cuckoo overlaps with only Prunella modularis or only Acrocephalus scirpaceus, respectively. 
#This may suggest that the cuckoo exploits different host species in different ecological contexts, or that local host availability varies along geographical and environmental gradients. 
#The black cells, where only the cuckoo is present, do not necessarily indicate a true absence of hosts. They may reflect the presence of other host species not included in this analysis, differences in sampling effort, or the greater mobility and detectability of Cuculus canorus. 
# In contrast, the light blue cells, where only the host species are present, show that host presence alone is not sufficient to determine cuckoo presence. Other factors, such as climate, habitat structure, host density, breeding phenology, and migratory constraints, may also influence the distribution of the cuckoo.
